Reasoning: The claim is strongly supported by evidence from a multicentre, randomised controlled trial (CLOTS trial 1, Paper ID: 11718220). This study, involving 2518 patients admitted to hospital with acute stroke, found no significant reduction in deep vein thrombosis (DVT) with the use of thigh-length graduated compression stockings (GCS). Specifically, the primary outcome (occurrence of symptomatic or asymptomatic DVT) was 10.0% in the GCS group and 10.5% in the group avoiding GCS, an absolute risk reduction of 0.5% (95% CI -1.9% to 2.9%), which was not statistically significant. The study concluded that these data do not support the use of thigh-length GCS in this patient population. Furthermore, the study reported significantly more skin breaks, ulcers, blisters, and skin necrosis in patients allocated to GCS.
